    <h1 class="page-title">About</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">Physics, mathematics, markets, and a habit of explaining.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I am Leonardo David Solis Rodríguez, an undergraduate physics student at
        UNAM's Faculty of Sciences in Mexico City. My interests sit between
        experimental quantum physics, applied mathematics, and the structure
        of electricity markets.
      </p>

      <h2>Research</h2>
      <p>
        At LAFriOC (Instituto de Física, UNAM) I work on cold-atom experiments —
        right now, four-wave mixing as a quantum memory system. I care about
        the instrument as much as the theory: designing the apparatus is
        half the experiment.
      </p>

      <h2>Quant</h2>
      <p>
        Professionally I have worked as a transmission analyst on electricity
        markets pipelines (PostgreSQL, Pandas, Polars), including a CRR
        attribution layer. I am drawn to problems where statistical physics
        and market microstructure overlap — Random Matrix Theory in
        particular.
      </p>

      <h2>Teaching</h2>
      <p>
        I have been teaching since I was 17, both privately and at university
        (Computational Tools workshop, UNAM Faculty of Sciences). I founded
        Sequoia, a prep course for the ECOEMS high school admission exam.
      </p>

      <h2>Elsewhere</h2>
      <p>
        Code lives on <a href="https://github.com/">GitHub</a>. The site is
        the narrative around it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
